 Forecast Discussion







   SPC AC 281730

   Day 2 Convective Outlook  
   NWS Storm Prediction Center Norman OK
   1230 PM CDT Fri Jul 28 2017

   Valid 291200Z - 301200Z

   ...THERE IS A MARGINAL RISK OF SEVERE THUNDERSTORMS ACROSS PART OF
   THE SOUTHEAST STATES...

   ...THERE IS A MARGINAL RISK OF SEVERE THUNDERSTORMS FROM THE CENTRAL
   HIGH PLAINS TO WESTERN AND CENTRAL SD...

   ...SUMMARY...
   A few strong to severe storms are possible Saturday across portions
   of the Southeast, and from the central High Plains to western and
   central South Dakota.

   ...Synopsis...
   Eastern U.S. trough will shift slowly eastward to the Atlantic
   coast, while undergoing gradual weakening.  Heights are expected to
   rise from the Pacific Northwest to the northern Plains, as the
   western U.S. ridge strengthens.  Weak midlevel perturbations moving
   across the Great Basin, Southwest states, and into the central High
   Plains to the Dakotas will support thunderstorms.

   At the surface, high pressure will prevail across large portions of
   the country, in the wake of a cold front moving steadily across and
   off the Gulf and Atlantic Coast areas through the period.  This
   boundary will be a focus for thunderstorms, some strong to severe,
   from the eastern Carolinas to portions of the Gulf Coast states.

   ...Southeast states...
   Rich moisture (precipitable water around or exceeding 2 inches) will
   support moderate instability south of the cold front, despite the
   presence of weak lapse rates.  Strong effective bulk shear should
   remain north of this marginal risk area suggesting the potential for
   organized storms will be low.  Given the moist environment, isolated
   wet microbursts will be possible.

   ...Central High Plains to western and central SD...
   Southerly low-level winds across these areas will maintain a moist
   air mass with surface dew points in the 60s.  Although steeper
   midlevel lapse rates should be confined to areas west of the
   marginal risk, surface heating combined with the moist environment
   (precipitable water around 1.5 inches) should result in moderate
   instability (MLCAPE 1000-1500 J/kg).  Weak midlevel impulses
   tracking to the east/southeast across this marginal risk area
   Saturday afternoon and evening, despite height rises, are expected
   to support isolated to scattered storm development.  Vertically
   veering winds with effective bulk shear of 30-40 kt suggest
   multicell/supercell storms will be possible, though the weak
   midlevel lapse rates may tend to limit updraft strength and overall
   severe-weather threat.

   ..Peters.. 07/28/2017

