 Forecast Discussion






   SPC AC 290034

   Day 1 Convective Outlook  
   NWS Storm Prediction Center Norman OK
   0734 PM CDT Fri Jul 28 2017

   Valid 290100Z - 291200Z

   ...THERE IS A MARGINAL RISK OF SEVERE THUNDERSTORMS ACROSS PARTS OF
   THE CAROLINAS AND SOUTHEAST VIRGINIA...

   ...THERE IS A MARGINAL RISK OF SEVERE THUNDERSTORMS ACROSS PARTS OF
   THE SOUTHERN PLAINS EASTWARD INTO THE GULF COAST STATES...

   ...THERE IS A MARGINAL RISK OF SEVERE THUNDERSTORMS ACROSS PARTS OF
   THE CENTRAL HIGH PLAINS...

   ...SUMMARY...
   Thunderstorms associated with marginally severe wind gusts will be
   possible early this evening across the Carolinas and from the Gulf
   Coast States to the southern Plains. A few storms with marginally
   severe hail and strong wind gusts will also be possible across parts
   of the central High Plains.

   ...Carolinas/Southeast Virginia...
   The latest water vapor imagery shows a positively tilted upper-level
   trough over the lower Great Lakes into the Ohio Valley with a plume
   of mid-level moisture ahead of the system along the eastern
   Seaboard. Scattered thunderstorms are ongoing within this plume
   within a corridor of maximized low-level moisture from Georgia
   northeastward to eastern Virginia. According to the RAP, the
   stronger instability is located in the eastern Carolinas where
   surface dewpoints are in the mid to upper 70s F. Steep low-level
   lapse rates and moderate instability, mainly due to the high
   moisture content, may be sufficient for isolated marginally severe
   wind gusts for another hour or two.

   ...Southern Plains/Lower to Mid Mississippi Valley/Gulf Coast
   States...
   Surface analysis currently shows a cold front located from the Red
   River Valley eastward into the Tennessee Valley. Scattered
   thunderstorms are ongoing from near the front in southeastern
   Oklahoma eastward to Tennessee and the Gulf Coast States. Surface
   dewpoints in the mid 70s F along this corridor are contributing to
   moderate instability with the RAP estimating SBCAPE in the 2000 to
   3000 J/kg range. This combined with steep low-level lapse rates may
   be enough for a few marginally severe wind gusts over the next
   couple of hours.

   ...Central High Plains...
   The latest water vapor imagery shows an upper-level ridge in the
   northern Rockies with northwest mid-level flow over the High Plains.
   At the surface, a narrow zone of maximized low-level moisture exists
   from eastern Colorado northward into western Nebraska where the RAP
   is estimating SBCAPE in the 1000 to 2000 J/kg range. In addition,
   the WSR-88D VWPs at North Platte, NE and Goodland, CO show moderate
   deep-layer shear with substantial veering of the winds with height
   in the lowest 3 km. This may be enough for storm rotation within the
   stronger updrafts making hail and strong gusty winds possible early
   this evening.

   ..Broyles.. 07/29/2017

   CLICK TO GET WUUS01 PTSDY1 PRODUCT

   NOTE: THE NEXT DAY 1 OUTLOOK IS SCHEDULED BY 0600Z

        




